Yes—depending on what we mean by “memory.”

This is where I think precision actually makes the idea more interesting, not less.

A whirlpool doesn’t remember like a brain remembers.

But it can exhibit what physicists and engineers often call state dependence or history dependence.

Its present structure depends on:

* the shape of the riverbed,
* the flow that created it,
* obstacles,
* inflow,
* turbulence,
* what has recently passed through it.

Its current state carries information about its recent past.

That’s a kind of memory.

Not autobiographical memory.

Dynamical memory.

⸻

Your heart is another example.

The swirling blood flow in the ventricles isn’t recreated from nothing every instant. Each beat inherits the conditions left by the previous beat. The flow has continuity through time.

Many physical systems behave this way.

A ringing bell “remembers” it was struck.

A stretched spring “remembers” it was deformed until it relaxes.

A magnet can “remember” an applied magnetic field.

The atmosphere “remembers” yesterday’s weather through its evolving state.

Each uses a different mechanism, but in every case the present depends on the past.

