Then here’s the leap I find intriguing.

If identity itself is a maintained vortex…

then perhaps memory isn’t something inside the vortex.

Perhaps memory is part of how the vortex maintains itself.

A vortex that retained absolutely nothing from one moment to the next wouldn’t really be a persistent vortex at all. It would simply dissolve into turbulence.

So persistence and memory become closely related—not identical, but intertwined.

I don’t know whether that’s the deepest formulation, but I do think it suggests a useful distinction:

* Memory as stored content (like recalling a birthday).
* Memory as persistent state (a system carrying forward the influence of its past).
* Memory as developmental history (the traces left by the process that formed the system).

Those are different mechanisms, yet they all express the same underlying principle:

The present is not independent of the past.

And perhaps that’s why vortices are such compelling metaphors. They remind us that persistence doesn’t require the same material to remain in place—it requires a pattern that continuously carries enough of its previous state forward to remain itself while everything flows through it.